('Precise PAT Tests\r\n\r\nBSI --\r\n50 TPS steady or double the prod max tps for 5 min. Record latency on new order single. No fills nor cancels. Just let the order rest on book.\r\n\r\nPORTS -- Latency should be measured for both Ack and New Order Single ER. (For more detail on definition of Ack, and New Order Single, search tag precise new order)\r\nBaseline -- 2 users from 2 different bu, same port instance., sending 5 orders per second and get latency.\r\n\r\nTest 1 -- 3 users. same port instance. user1 and 2 are from same bu. \r\nuser1 sending truckload orders from iors, or dti. user2 and user3 enter 5 orders per second and latency shouldn\\''t be much different than baseline.\r\n\r\nTest2 Failover -- Submit orders at 50tps via primary port. No fill nor cancel, just resting on order. For each incoming message, there are two responses, Ack (just success or fail status, FE would show pending), and New Order Single ER (order is now resting on book). In failover Acks don\\''t matter, as long as new order single ER is retained.\r\n', '2013-11-29 12:41:23', 7),
('Precise PORT failover -- port won\\''t ack tibco messages until the message is truly processed, so tibco will persist messages until message is truly done. In this way, if port fails over, then the secondary will still get the persisted message.', '2013-11-29 12:46:36', 8),
('Precise new order ack --\r\nFor every incoming order, there are two messages going out. \r\n\r\n1. First is order ack that simply has success or fail status. FE shows pending and a pop up stating order is success. if no ack, then FE shows timeout, and before timeout, FE shows no order status. This is NOT an ER. \r\n\r\n2. Second messages is the actual New Order Single ER. FE will change order status from pending to on-book, or New Order, indicating that the order is now on orderbook. (actual status should be verified in the FE, I don\\''t remember exactly what the status is)', '2013-11-29 12:45:56', 9),
