('MYSQL\\''s reads are no lock by default --\r\nThe default isolation level is -- read committed\r\nOne can also set the level to read uncommitted. But both don\\''t lock table\r\n\r\nSET SESSION TRANSACTION ISOLATION LEVEL READ UNCOMMITTED ;\r\n\r\nHere\\''s the difference between the two --\r\nThe difference is In Read Uncommitted mode the user sees dirty reads (means data that is not yet committed by other sessions)\r\n\r\nThis does not happen with Read committed. IN READ COMMITTED isolation level, the rows returned by a query are the rows that were committed when the query was started.\r\n\r\nDetail description --\r\nhttps://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.0/en/set-transaction.html#isolevel_read-uncommitted', '2014-02-18 16:41:25', 83),
